{"label":"Data Structure & Algorithm","id":"dsa","list":[{"label":"Multiple Choice Question","type":"mcq","id":"test","commonData":{"title":"Multiple Choice Question","allowFrac":false},"data":[{"questions":[{"qText":"Which data structure uses FIFO (First In First Out) principle?","options":"queue\nstack\narray\ntree"},{"qText":"Which data structure uses LIFO (Last In First Out) principle?","options":"stack\nqueue\nlinked list\ngraph"},{"qText":"Which of the following is a linear data structure?","options":"array\ntree\ngraph\nhash table"},{"qText":"Which of the following is a non-linear data structure?","options":"tree\nstack\nqueue\narray"},{"qText":"What is the time complexity of binary search in a sorted array?","options":"O(log n)\nO(n)\nO(n log n)\nO(1)"}]},{"questions":[{"qText":"Which traversal of a binary search tree gives sorted output?","options":"inorder\npreorder\npostorder\nlevel order"},{"qText":"Which data structure is used in recursion?","options":"stack\nqueue\nheap\ngraph"},{"qText":"Which algorithm is used to find the shortest path in a graph?","options":"Dijkstra's algorithm\nKruskal's algorithm\nmerge sort\nquick sort"},{"qText":"Which of the following is a divide and conquer algorithm?","options":"merge sort\nbubble sort\ninsertion sort\nselection sort"},{"qText":"Which of the following is not a stable sorting algorithm?","options":"selection sort\nmerge sort\ninsertion sort\nbubble sort"}]},{"questions":[{"qText":"What is the maximum number of children a binary tree node can have?","options":"2\n1\n3\n4"},{"qText":"Which data structure is best for implementing priority queues?","options":"heap\nstack\narray\nlinked list"},{"qText":"Which searching algorithm works only on sorted data?","options":"binary search\nlinear search\nhashing\ndfs"},{"qText":"Which data structure is used in breadth-first search (BFS) of a graph?","options":"queue\nstack\npriority queue\nhash table"},{"qText":"Which traversal technique visits root, then left, then right in a binary tree?","options":"preorder\ninorder\npostorder\nlevel order"}]}]},{"label":"Drag and Drop","id":"drag-drop","type":"matchByDragDrop","data":{"fontSize":"1.3rem","dashWidth":80,"text":"A linear structure where elements are connected using pointers (nodes) : *Linked List*\nStores elements in key–value pairs for fast lookup : *Hash Table*\nElements are stored in contiguous memory locations, accessed by index : *Array*\nInsertion and deletion follow LIFO (Last In First Out) principle : *Stack*\nInsertion and deletion follow FIFO (First In First Out) principle : *Queue*\nRepeatedly compares adjacent elements and swaps them if needed : *Bubble Sort*\nA hierarchical structure with nodes having left/right children : *Binary Tree*\nSearches a sorted array by repeatedly dividing the search interval in half : *Binary Search* "}},{"type":"classifySentence","label":"True or False","id":"true-false","data":{"title":"True or False","types":[{"name":"True","text":"An array is a linear data structure.\nA stack follows the Last In First Out principle.\nA queue follows the First In First Out principle.\nInorder traversal of a Binary Search Tree gives elements in sorted order.\nMerge sort works on the divide and conquer principle."},{"name":"False","text":"A binary tree node can have more than two children.\nBinary search can be applied on unsorted data.\nA graph cannot have cycles.\nSelection sort is always faster than merge sort for large data sets.\nBreadth first search uses a stack for implementation."}]}},{"id":"fillup","label":"Fill in the blanks","type":"fillup","data":{"title":"Fill in the blanks","fontSize":"1.4rem","text":"A *stack (queue, array)* follows the Last In First Out principle.\n        A *queue (stack, tree)* follows the First In First Out principle.\n        The traversal of a Binary Search Tree that gives elements in sorted order is *inorder (preorder, postorder)*.\n        The data structure used in recursion is *stack (queue, heap)*.\n        The best data structure for implementing priority queues is *heap (linked list, array)*.\n*Merge sort (Bubble sort, Insertion sort)* is a divide and conquer algorithm.\nThe maximum number of children a node can have in a binary tree is *2 (3, 4)*.\nThe data structure used in breadth-first search (BFS) is *queue (stack, priority queue)*.\nThe traversal technique of a binary tree that visits root, then left, then right is *preorder (inorder, postorder) *."}}]}